<Prose
  title="About this site"
  description="The Art of Geomancy presents medieval and Renaissance geomancy straight from the historical sources, fully cited: a reference for students of the authentic tradition."
  crumbs={[{ name: 'About' }]}
>
  <p>
    This site is a reference library for students of traditional geomancy. Its premise is simple:
    the art is best learned from the authors who practised it. Every interpretive statement here
    (the meanings of the sixteen figures, their judgments in the twelve houses, the techniques of
    reading a chart) is quoted directly from the public-domain historical sources, with a citation
    and, wherever possible, a link to the very page of the original edition it was transcribed
    from.
  </p>
  <h2>The sources</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Christopher Cattan, <em>The Geomancie</em> (English translation by Francis Sparry, London 1591)</li>
    <li>John Heydon, <em>Theomagia, or the Temple of Wisdome</em> (London 1663–4)</li>
    <li>Henry Cornelius Agrippa (attrib.), <em>Of Geomancy</em>, trans. Robert Turner (London 1655)</li>
    <li>Gerard of Cremona (attrib.), <em>Of Astronomical Geomancy</em>, trans. Robert Turner (London 1655)</li>
    <li>Aleister Crowley, <em>A Handbook of Geomancy</em> (The Equinox I.2, London 1909)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The first four are works of the medieval and Renaissance tradition proper; Crowley's handbook
    is included as the most influential modern synthesis, and because its tables preserve material
    found nowhere else in print. See <a href={withBase('/about/editorial-method/')}>the editorial method</a>
    for how the texts are transcribed and what has been normalised.
  </p>
  <h2>What this site is not</h2>
  <p>
    It is not a manual of modern eclectic divination. Where modern practice differs from the old
    books, the old books are given. Where the old books differ from each other (and they do, down
    to the elements and signs of the figures), the differences are shown rather than smoothed
    over.
  </p>
</Prose>
